title: (alpha,pxn) reactions on natural gadolinium.

x4freetext: (alpha,pxn) reactions on natural gadolinium.

x4codes.hlp: Consejo Nac. de Invest. Cientificas y Tec. (CONICET), Argentina

x4freetext: The Gd foils were analyzed spectroscopically, and the
impurities were negligible.  The surface density of
these foils was about 19.0 mg/cm2.  Each one of the
foils constituting a target was wrapped in Al of
surface density 3.72 mg/cm2, in order to avoid the loss
of radioactive nuclei by recoiling.

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Journal of Radioanalytical and Nuclear Chemistry, Vol.152, p.189 (1991)
Jour: Journal of Inorganic and Nuclear Chemistry, Vol.36, p.3647 (1974)
Jour: Journal of the Physical Society of Japan, Vol.56, p.3135 (1987)

x4freetext: Cu foils were interleaved between the Gd foils.
Irradtation and cooling times were not given.
Beam current was varied between 5 and 8 muA.
The uncertainties in the cross sections arise
essentially from the errors in the peak area and the
efficiency calibration.  The authors considered the
data to have an overall error of 15%.
The uncertainty of Gd foils thickness.  No
corrections due to the nonunifonnity of the foils
thicknesses were made.
Error due to angular straggling.
The error in flux determination is less
than 11% whereas fluxes obtained through both standard
functions differ only in 1%
-By authors.  Assuming a cross section of 2 barn, the
loss of intensity in the last foil of the target is
approximately 6%.  Therefore, this effect was
neglected.  It was not necessary to take into account
corrections due to eventual losses of reaction products
by recoil, as each target foil was wrapped in aluminium
and the products trapped in the catcher were measured
with the gadolinium foils.
The resultes were compared with the excitation
functions calculated through the COMPLEX code,
based in the INCLUSIVE and EXCLUSIVE INDEX MODEL.
By F.Ch
Last checking has been done.
